{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"9bb80250-0782-434a-a9c7-bde0c1725a71","content":"In modern MSTest (3.8+), you can inject `TestContext` via the constructor and use `IAsyncLifetime` for async initialization. Here's the recommended pattern:\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests : IAsyncLifetime\n{\n    public TestContext TestContext { get; }\n\n    // Synchronous init via constructor\n    public MyTests(TestContext testContext)\n    {\n        TestContext = testContext;\n        // sync setup here (e.g., create objects, set fields)\n    }\n\n    // Async init (runs before each test)\n    public async Task InitializeAsync()\n    {\n        // async setup here (e.g., DB connections, HTTP clients)\n        await Task.CompletedTask;\n    }\n\n    public async Task DisposeAsync()\n    {\n        // async cleanup\n        await Task.CompletedTask;\n    }\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public void ExampleTest()\n    {\n        Assert.IsNotNull(TestContext);\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **Constructor injection** — MSTest 3.x injects `TestContext` automatically via the constructor parameter (no need for the old `[TestInitialize]` property setter).\n- **`IAsyncLifetime`** — Implement this interface for async setup/teardown. `InitializeAsync` runs before each test, `DisposeAsync` after.\n- **Execution order**: Constructor → `InitializeAsync` → Test → `DisposeAsync`.\n\nThis replaces the older `[TestInitialize]`/`[TestCleanup]` attribute pattern and gives you both sync and async hooks cleanly.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"0a07eb7d-6863-42da-9d5b-88dbfa127cdd","outputTokens":391,"requestId":"BD0C:93C8B:1DFEF40:21EC93D:6A07CBB2"},"id":"0ca52488-d492-4a98-8e68-f3bf586349c9","timestamp":"2026-05-16T01:43:25.712Z","parentId":"c7571b9f-db1a-4e47-aa65-ff8e6d888db1"}
